},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to her local hospital with a one-week history of worsening productive cough, dyspnoea, and fevers. She has a medical history of COPD, hypertension, and three prior myocardial infarctions with four stents in situ. Her regular medications include amlodipine. She has a 35 pack-year smoking history and is an active smoker. On examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is started on intravenous antibiotics, prednisolone, and nebulisers. She improves symptomatically and is discharged for rehabilitation after one week. She is now back to baseline functioning according to the physiotherapist. However, she has remained hypoxic, with oxygen saturation 90% on room air, dropping to 87% on mobilising. She saturates at 98% on 2 L/min oxygen via nasal cannulae. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there are scattered wheezes and scant bibasal crepitations. Dual heart sounds are heard with no added murmurs. The apex beat is displaced to the anterior axillary line. JVP is not raised. There is no hepatosplenomegaly, peripheral oedema, ascites or caput medusae. Calves are soft and non-tender. Her ECG is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her hypoxia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incompletely resolved chest infection","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Right-sided heart failure","Ischaemic heart disease","Pulmonary embolism"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHypoxaemia is a very common finding among patients with \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)\u003C/strong\u003E, arising primarily due to ventilation/perfusion mismatch caused by progressive airflow limitation and destruction of pulmonary capillaries. In this case, the patient\u0027s acceptable oxygen saturations could reasonably be modified to a target range of 88-92%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient initially presented with an acute infective exacerbation of COPD, as evidenced by increased productive cough, dyspnoea and fever. She was treated with intravenous antibiotics, steroids and nebulisers. While an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincompletely resolved chest infection\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially contribute to ongoing hypoxia, the history suggests she has improved back to her baseline, making this less likely to be the predominant cause compared to her underlying COPD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG demonstrates features of left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH), with the Sokolov-Lyon voltage criteria fulfilled (S wave amplitude in V1 + R wave amplitude in V5 or V6 \u003E 35 mm). This is consistent with the displaced apex beat on examination, likely resulting from her known cardiovascular disease. However, there are only mild bibasal crepitations and no other signs of pulmonary oedema or left-sided heart failure that would account for hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, acute \u003Cstrong\u003Eischaemic heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E severe enough to cause hypoxaemia would likely manifest with pulmonary oedema and other features of acute heart failure, which are absent here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has no signs to suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Eright-sided heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E, such as raised JVP, hepatosplenomegaly, peripheral oedema, ascites or caput medusae. Isolated right heart failure would also not typically cause hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E should always be considered as a cause of hypoxaemia, there are no specific features in this case to raise clinical suspicion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is associated with chronic hypoxaemia due to ventilation/perfusion mismatch.","The Sokolov-Lyon voltage criteria are commonly used to diagnose left ventricular hypertrophy on ECG: S wave amplitude in V1 + R wave amplitude in V5 or V6 \u003E 35 mm"],"references":["Kent BD, Mitchell PD, McNicholas WT. Hypoxemia in patients with COPD: cause, effects, and disease progression. Int J Chron Obstruct Pulmon Dis. 2011;6:199-208. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3107696/","Bacharova L, Estes EH. Left Ventricular Hypertrophy by the Surface ECG. J Electrocardiol. 2017;50(6):906-908. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28651797/#:~:text=Abstract,altered%20QRS%20and%20T%20patterns."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30834"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1776"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"12349"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"12349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/12349"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2421d47c-b4e1-4690-9f23-2654f0a18fba.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2421d47c-b4e1-4690-9f23-2654f0a18fba.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":591}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30834"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-22T21:28:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-22T21:29:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1776"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45892"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag